TY  - JOUR
AB  - This paper, save for minor textual changes and footnote additions covering developments through February, 1939, was read at the Round Table on The R&#xf4;le of Public Investment and Consumer Capital Formation, at the Fifty-first Annual Meeting of the American Economic Association in Detroit, Michigan, December 28, 1938. In considering the effect of government competition upon private investment, the important current issue relates to the invasion by the government of selected " non-competitive" areas. The best example is the field of electric power, where point-by-point competition on a broad front cannot permanently obtain. Background considerations relating to the character of the industry, the power of the government, the government's over-all purpose, and the regulatory possibilities of government competition should be borne in mind. Private investors will be affected by their belief as to the government's purpose, and its special capacities and tactics. If government competition proceeds solely on its economic merits, fairly represented and understood, its effects need not be different from the effects of private competition. Government competition vigorously and intelligently conducted as a supplement to administrative regulation may force private electricrates to government-determined levels and may invigorate both the industry and the agencies of regulation: it may well produce such lowered rates and widened use, and such an increase in private investment as would have resulted if administrative regulation had been really effective.
